05625nam a22009855i 9781487527594DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875275947 a10.3138/97814875275942doi  a(DE-B1597)583314  a(OCoLC)1240820011  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDB98.S3bR86 2021 7aHIS0400002bisacsh04a943.605/120922231 aRummel, Erika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrison Elite :bHow Austrian Chancellor Kurt Schuschnigg Survived Nazi Captivity /cErika Rummel. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one In Isolation: Living under the Enemy’s Eye -- tChapter two The Sachsenhausen Household: Living en famille -- tChapter three The Comfort of Religion -- tChapter four The Consolation of Books -- tChapter five Music to His Ears -- tChapter six The Use of Wit -- tChapter seven Cherishing Memories -- tChapter eight Schuschnigg’s Political Reminiscences -- tConclusion -- tAppendix Chronology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the Anschluss (annexation) in 1938, the Nazis forced Austrian Chancellor Kurt Schuschnigg to resign and kept him imprisoned for seven years, until his rescue by the Allies in 1945. Schuschnigg’s privileged position within the concentration camp system allowed him to keep a diary and to write letters which were smuggled out to family members. Drawing on these records, Prison Elite paints a picture of a little-known aspect of concentration camp history: the life of a VIP prisoner. Schuschnigg, who was a devout Catholic, presents his memoirs as a "confession," expecting absolution for any political missteps and, more specifically, for his dictatorial regime in the 1930s. As Erika Rummel reveals in fascinating detail, his autobiographical writings are frequently unreliable. Prison Elite describes the strategies Schuschnigg used to survive his captivity emotionally and intellectually. Religion, memory of better days, friendship, books and music, and maintaining a sense of humour allowed him to cope. A comparison with the memoirs of fellow captives reveals these tactics to be universal. Studying Schuschnigg’s writing in the context of contemporary prison memoirs, Prison Elite provides unique insight into the life of a VIP prisoner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aStatesmenzAustriavBiography. 0aStatesmenzAustriaxCorrespondence. 0aStatesmenzAustriaxDiaries. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration camps. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, GermanvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, GermanxCorrespondence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, GermanxDiaries. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh  aAnschluss.  aAustria.  aAustrian chancellor.  aGermany.  aHolocaust.  aKurt Schuschnigg.  aNazi prison.  aSachsenhausen.  aVIP prisoner.  aWWII.  aWorld War Two.  aconcentration camps.  acoping strategies.  aelite prisoner.  aprison memoirs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978